## Natural Emerald Cut Engagement Ring: Prices and Total Ring Costs

Natural GIA-certified emerald cut diamonds start at roughly $3,000 for a 1ct G-VS1 in certified inventory. Entry-quality grades at 1ct that are eye-clean and GIA-certified typically run $2,800–$3,500 depending on the specific colour-clarity combination. D colour at 1ct natural emerald starts significantly higher because the emerald cut's large open table shows body warmth more readily than a brilliant cut — buyers paying for D colour are paying for the assurance of full colourlessness in that open window.

[![Emerald cut diamond engagement ring yellow gold solitaire with melee band](https://ion.bluenile.com/sets/Jewelry/Photoshoot/Bluenile/BrioPackshotBox/Rings/501150/501150_M1_EMR_DIM_wht_0100CT_Y_Box5_003_1600X1600.jpg)](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings?MetalType=all&Diamonds=Dia&ShapeID=Emerald&a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)

<table class="dc-custom-table"><thead><tr><th>Diamond</th><th>Cert</th><th>Colour / Clarity</th><th>Stone Price</th><th>+ Riviera Pavé WG $1,515</th><th>Total Ring</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-search?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational">1ct Natural Emerald</a></td><td>GIA</td><td>D / VS1</td><td><strong>$3,140</strong></td><td>+ $1,515</td><td><strong>$4,655</strong></td></tr><tr><td><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-search?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational">1.5ct Natural Emerald</a></td><td>GIA</td><td>E / VS1</td><td><strong>$10,409</strong></td><td>+ $1,515</td><td><strong>$11,924</strong></td></tr><tr><td><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-search?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational">2ct Natural Emerald</a></td><td>GIA</td><td>F / VS1</td><td><strong>$24,407</strong></td><td>+ $1,515</td><td><strong>$25,922</strong></td></tr><tr><td><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-search?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational">3ct Natural Emerald</a></td><td>GIA</td><td>F / VS1</td><td><strong>$63,574</strong></td><td>+ $1,515</td><td><strong>$65,089</strong></td></tr></tbody></table>

**Reading the natural table.** The 1ct D-VS1 at $4,655 total is the entry point for buyers who want the highest colour grade in GIA-certified natural. D colour at 1ct in an emerald cut is visible — this shape shows colour more readily than any brilliant cut, and the open table at 1ct face-up (approximately 7.7mm × 5.7mm) lets the body warmth of F and below show under certain lighting conditions. VS1 is the minimum clarity for emerald cuts: the step-cut open table makes SI1 inclusions visible to the naked eye, and VS2 requires video verification.

The jump from 1ct ($4,655 total) to 1.5ct ($11,924 total) is $7,269 — the emerald cut's carat weight premium scales aggressively because large, inclusion-free emerald cut rough is genuinely scarce. The 2ct natural at $25,922 and the 3ct at $65,089 are luxury-tier purchases where the price reflects rough scarcity, not just weight.

> "The natural emerald cut market is one of the most unforgiving clarity markets in diamond retail. The step-cut facets act like mirrors — they show you everything inside the stone. I never recommend natural emerald cuts below VS1 without HD video confirmation, and for 2ct and above I want VS1 minimum even after video review.
>
> The price jump from 1ct to 1.5ct in natural — from $3,140 to $10,409 for the stone alone — is the steepest size step in the natural emerald cut market. If a natural 1.5ct is beyond budget, I tell buyers to go to 1ct with a better quality grade rather than stretch to 1.5ct with compromised clarity. The hall-of-mirrors effect requires an internally clean stone to work. A VS2 or SI1 natural emerald cut at 1.5ct can look foggy and dull rather than elegant and reflective." — Farzana Hasan, **[Diamond Critics](https://diamondcritics.com/about-farzana/)**

